#Text=Wheelchair Rugby Tri-Nations Series begins in Sydney
#Text=Friday , September 20 , 2013
#Text=Cathedral Square , Sydney , Australia — Wikinews attended the Wheelchair Rugby Tri-Nations Series in Cathedral Square , Sydney , ongoing from Wednesday .
#Text=This is the first time an international wheelchair rugby event has been held outdoors , and in this arena .
#Text=Three nations are competing : the United States , Australia , and New Zealand .
#Text=America 's Josh Wheeler Image : Jeff Crow Australian Paralympic Committee .

#Text=Left to right : Chuck Aoki ( US ) , Andrew Harrison ( Aus ) , Cameron Carr ( Aus ) , Jeremy Brown ( US ) , Ryan Scott ( Aus ) , Derrick Helton ( US ) Image : Jeff Crow Australian Paralympic Committee .
#Text=Wheelchair Rugby in Cathedral Square , Sydney .
#Text=Hyde Park and the Centrepoint Tower can be seen in the background .
#Text=Image : Hawkeye7 .
#Text=United States National Wheelchair
#Text=Rugby team Image : Hawkeye7 .
#Text=Justice Crew performs Image : Hawkeye7 .
#Text=Premier of New South Wales Barry O'Farrell and CEO of the Australian Paralympic Committee Jason Hellwig Image : Hawkeye7 .
#Text=The venue is Cathedral Square , Sydney , which is adjacent to Hyde Park .
#Text=The Sydney Central Business district is on the other side of the park .
#Text=An outdoor stadium has been constructed specifically for the tournament , which is believed to be the first time an international wheelchair rugby tournament has been held outdoors .
#Text=This choice was validated by the fine and warm weather .
#Text=Free sunscreen was given to the crowd .
#Text=The Opening Ceremony was officiated by Australian Paralympic Committee Chief Executive Officer Jason Hellwig .
#Text=In attendance were the Premier of New South Wales , Barry O'Farrell , the Deputy Lord Mayor of Sydney , Robyn Kemmis , and Paralympic swimmer Matthew Cowdrey .
#Text=A large crowd , mostly consisting of school groups , was entertained by boy band Justice Crew singing their hit Best Night .
#Text=Each team is to play the others two twice , on Wednesday September 18 and Thursday September 19 .
#Text=Finals are to be held on Friday .
#Text=All three teams are highly ranked internationally .
#Text=The United States team is ranked number one in the world .

#Text=It won bronze at the 2004 Summer Paralympics in Athens , gold at the 2008 Summer Paralympics in Beijing , and bronze at the 2012 Summer Paralympics in London , and is the current world champion .
#Text=This is its first visit to Australia since the 2000 Summer Paralympics .
#Text=The Australian team , known as the Steelers , is ranked second in the world .
#Text=It won silver in Beijing and gold in London .
#Text=The team is almost unchanged from the one that won in London .
#Text=Greg Smith has become the assistant coach .
#Text=The first game , held immediately after the Opening Ceremony , was between the United States and Australia .
#Text=The United States proved the better team , forcing errors and turnovers .
#Text=Three turnovers in the first quarter were especially costly for the Steelers , who lost 56 – 43 .
#Text=The second game was held at 17:30 under lights .
#Text=The crowd was small , but there were a number of New Zealand fans in the crowd , including a few Maori .
#Text=Two of the New Zealand players are also Maori .
#Text=The well-disciplined United States team proved too good for the Wheel Blacks as well , who lost 58 – 40 in an entertaining contest .
#Text=The third game was at 19:30 , between Australia and New Zealand .
#Text=The Australians led the whole game , which was nonetheless entertaining to the last .

#Text=In the dying seconds of the game , Australia 's Ryley Batt shunted a stalling New Zealand player across the line to force him to score , then threw the ball to team mate Chris Bond , who raced for the line at high speed but was beaten by the buzzer .
#Text=Australia won 61 – 48 .
#Text=The New Zealand team , known as the Wheel Blacks , is ranked tenth in the world .
#Text=It won gold in Athens .
#Text=Highlights of the tournament are scheduled to be shown on Foxtel Sports in Australia on September 28 and 29 .
